-list-of-winners-in-telugu-cinema/articleshow/72920660.cms|title=66th Yamaha Fascino Filmfare Awards South: Full List of Winners in Telugu Cinema - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=22 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222053917/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/66th-yamaha-fascino-filmfare-awards-south-full-list-of-winners-in-telugu-cinema/articleshow/72920660.cms|archive-date=22 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|4921260}}\n\n{{FilmfareSouthCriticsBestActor}}\n{{Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor}}\n{{SIIMA Award for Best Male D\u00e9butante}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salmaan, Dulquer}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Tamil cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kochi]]\n[[Category:Indian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards South winners]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:SIIMA Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Kerala State Film Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "112.134.4.92", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(No needed Info)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dulquer_Salmaan"}
{"title_page": "Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Komala Kurdistan's Organization of the Communist Party of Iran}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Komala\n| logo = The Official Logo Of Komala.png\n| logo_size = 100px\n| caption = [[Red star]] combined with the Soviet-style typography of Komala in Persian script<ref name=\"Detsch\">{{citation|last1=Detsch|first1=Jack|title=Kurdish rebels join anti-Iran lobbying fray|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/10/kurdish-rebels-anti-iran-lobbying.html|date=2 October 2018|work=Al-Monitor|accessdate=30 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002234856/https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/10/kurdish-rebels-anti-iran-lobbying.html|archive-date=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n| colorcode = Red\n| abbreviation = K\u015eZK\n| leader = [[Abdullah Mohtadi]]<ref name=\"MERIA\"/>\n| foundation = Originally {{start date and age|1969}}<br>Refounded in {{start date and age|2000}}\n| split = [[Komalah (CPI)]] (2000)\n| merged = [[Communist Party of Iran]] (1984)\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]<br>'''Historical:'''<br>[[Maoism]] <small>(1969\u20131979)</small>\n| headquarters = [[Sulaymaniyah]], [[Kurdistan Region]]\n| international = [[Socialist International]] (Observer)<br>[[Progressive Alliance (political international)|Progressive Alliance]]<br>[[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization|UNPO]]\n| website = [http://www.komalainternational.org/ Komala]\n| country = Iran\n| country2 = Iraq\n| founder = \n| position = [[Far-left politics|Far-left]]\n| national = [[Congress of Nationalities for a Federal Iran]]\n| colors = {{color box|#E70A0A}} Red\n| flag = [[File:Flag of Komala.png|200px]]\n| membership = <1,000 (estimate)<ref name=\"Milburn\"/>\n| membership_year = 2017\n}}\n\nThe '''Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan''' ({{lang-ku|{{lang|fa|\u0643\u06c6\u0645\u0647\u200c\u06b5\u0647\u200c\u06cc \u0634\u06c6\u0695\u0634\u06af\u06ce\u0695\u06cc \u0632\u0647\u200c\u062d\u0645\u0647\u200c\u062a\u0643\u06ce\u0634\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0643\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0626\u06ce\u0631\u0627\u0646}}|Kome\u0142ey \u015eorri\u015fg\u00earr\u00ee Zehmetk\u00ea\u015fan\u00ee Kurdistan\u00ee \u00caran|lit=Society of Revolutionary Toilers of Iranian Kurdistan}}), commonly shortened to '''Komalah''' ({{lang-ku|Kome\u0142e}}; {{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0648\u0645\u0644\u0647}}), is an armed [[communist]] [[ethnic party]] of [[Kurds in Iran]], currently exiled in northern [[Iraq]].<ref name=\"MERIA\"/> \n\nThe group is currently proscribed as a [[terrorist organization]] by [[Japan]], aside from Iran. Since 2018, it is registered [[Lobbying in the United States|lobby in the United States]].\n\nKomalah has been engaged in guerrilla warfare against the Iranian government, notably during the [[1979 Kurdish rebellion in Iran|1979 Kurdish rebellion]] and the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]. It was also [[KDPI\u2013Komala conflict|involved in armed conflict]] against the [[Democratic Party of Iranian Kurdistan]] (KDPI) during the 1980s and early 1990s.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Structure of Kurdish Society and the Struggle for a Kurdish State|author=Hussein Tahiri|year=2007|publisher=Mazda Publications|volume=8|series=Bibliotheca Iranica: Kurdish studies series|isbn=9781568591933|page=144}}</ref> After a long time peace, organisation declared to start armed struggle again in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kurdish party resumes armed struggle against Iran, third party to do so |url=https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/iran/30042017 |website=Rudaw |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe organization has \"no strong influence among the Kurds in Iran\", according to Rodi Hevian.<ref name=\"MERIA\">{{cite journal|author=Rodi Hevian|title=THE MAIN KURDISH POLITICAL PARTIES IN IRAN, IRAQ, SYRIA, AND TURKEY: A RESEARCH GUIDE|url=http://www.rubincenter.org/2013/08/the-main-kurdish-political-parties-in-iran-iraq-syria-and-turkey-a-research-guide/|date=Summer 2013|volume=17|journal=[[Middle East Review of International Affairs]]|number=2|publisher=Rubin Center for Research in International Affairs|location= Herzliya, Israel}}</ref>\n== History ==\nIt is not known when exactly the organization began its activity.<ref>{{citation|first=Ali|last=Ezzatyar|title=The Last Mufti of Iranian Kurdistan: Ethnic and Religious Implications in the Greater Middle East|date=2016|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137563248|page=35}}</ref> According to the account of [[Abdullah Mohtadi]], together with six other Kurdish students in [[Tehran]], he co-founded the group on 27 October 1969 at a secret initiation meeting.<ref>{{citation|first=Ali|last=Ezzatyar|title=The Last Mufti of Iranian Kurdistan: Ethnic and Religious Implications in the Greater Middle East|date=2016|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137563248|page=104}}</ref> [[Ladislav Bittman]] wrote in ''[[The KGB and Soviet Disinformation]]'' that Komala was part of [[KGB]]'s network in Iran, and was founded under financial and ideological influence of [[Soviet Union]].<ref>{{citation|first=Ladislav|last=Bittman|title=The KGB and Soviet Disinformation: An Insider's View|url=https://archive.org/details/TheKGBAndSovietDisinformationLadislavBittman|publisher=Pergamon-Brassey's|year=1983|isbn=9780080315720|page=111}}</ref> [[Edgar O'Ballance]] states that Komala received \"help\" from the Soviet KGB.<ref>{{citation|first=Edgar|last=O'Ballance|journal=Military Review: The Professional Journal of the United States Army|title=The Kurdish Factor in the Gulf War|volume=61|number=6|date=June 1981|page=16}}</ref>\n\nThe organization operated underground, and only went into public after the [[Iranian Revolution]] in 1979.<ref name=\"Kreyenbroek and Sperl\"/> In September 1983, the group underwent organizational changes and patterned itself as an orthodox communist party, eventually joining [[Communist Party of Iran]], as its [[Komalah (CPI)|Kurdish wing]].<ref name=\"NE\"/> In 2000, the faction led by [[Abdullah Mohtadi]] split from the latter and styled itself as the \"original\" Komala.<ref>{{citation|last1=Romano|first1=David|last2=Gurses|first2=Mehmet|title=Conflict, Democratization, and the Kurds in the Middle East: Turkey, Iran, Iraq, and Syria|date=2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-40999-7|page=75|edition=1st|doi=10.1057/9781137409997_4}}</ref>\n\nOn grounds that politburo acts non-democratic, the faction led by Omar Ilkhanizade split in October 2007, founding [[Organization of the Toilers of Kurdistan|the faction of reform]].<ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\">{{citation|first1=Hashem|last1=Ahmadzadeh|first2=Gareth|last2=Stansfield|title=The Political, Cultural, and Military Re-Awakening of the Kurdish Nationalist Movement in Iran|journal=Middle East Journal|volume=64|number=1|date=2010|pages=11-27|jstor=20622980}}</ref> On 29 April 2008, another faction led by Abdulla Konaposhi accused Mohtadi of \"non-democratic management\", and expressing dissatifcation to a policy of a cooperation with [[Monarchism in Iran|monarchists]] including [[Reza Pahlavi, Crown Prince of Iran|Reza Pahlavi]], split from the group to establish [[Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan\u2013Reunification Faction|the reunification faction]].<ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\"/>\n\n== Ideology ==\nThe group is ideologically [[Marxist\u2013Leninist]], therefore it saw itself [[revolutionary]] and transcending ethnic boundaries, unlike rival [[Democratic Party of Iranian Kurdistan]].<ref name=\"NE\">{{cite book|last=Entessar|first=Nader|title=Kurdish Politics in the Middle East|publisher=Lexington Books|location=Lanham|page=49\u201350|year=2010|isbn=9780739140390|oclc=430736528}}</ref> It was predominantly [[Maoist]] during first decade of its activity<ref name=\"NE\"/> and adopted it as a [[Theory of National Struggle|mobilization strategy]] to recruit from peasantry and lower urban class.<ref>{{cite book|last=Romano|first=David|title=The Kurdish Nationalist Movement: Opportunity, Mobilization and Identity|series=Cambridge Middle East studies, 22.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2006|page=233|isbn=978-0-521-85041-4|oclc=61425259}}</ref> However at its first congress held in 1979, the ideology was renounced due to being \"inappropriate to Kurdish conditions in Iran\".<ref name=\"NE\"/> In 1981, the group initiated [[Self-criticism (Marxism\u2013Leninism)|self-criticism]] of its past and concluded that what it needs is \"strong links with the [[proletariat]]\".<ref name=\"Kreyenbroek and Sperl\">{{cite book|editor-last1=Kreyenbroek|editor-first1=Philip G.|editor-last2=Sperl|editor-first2=Stefan|title=The Kurds: A Contemporary Overview|publisher=Routledge|page=143|year=2005|isbn=9781134907663}}</ref>\n\n== Armed activities ==\n{{see also|1979 Kurdish rebellion in Iran|Iran\u2013Iraq War|KDPI\u2013Komala conflict|Western Iran clashes (2016\u2013present)}}\n\n== Designation as a terrorist organization ==\nThe following countries have listed Komola as a [[terrorist organization]]:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n!Country\n!{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Iran}}\n|<ref name=\"Milburn\">{{citation|first=Franc|last=Milburn|title=Iranian Kurdish Militias: Terrorist-Insurgents, Ethno Freedom Fighters, or Knights on the Regional Chessboard?|url=http://www.css.ethz.ch/en/services/digital-library/articles/article.html/41930fa0-6afa-42f3-837b-e343778df613/pdf|publisher=Combating Terrorism Center|via=Eidgen\u00f6ssische Technische Hochschule Z\u00fcrich|date=May 2017|volume=10|issue=5|journal=CTC Sentinel|pages=1\u20132}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Japan}}\n|<ref name=\"JPN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moj.go.jp/psia/ITH/organizations/ME_N-africa/komala.html |script-title=ja:\u30b3\u30de\u30e9|publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (Japan)|Ministry of Justice of Japan]] |language=ja |title=Komaleh\uff0cKumele|access-date=20 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190309091042/http://www.moj.go.jp/psia/ITH/organizations/ME_N-africa/komala.html|archive-date=9 March 2019|url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|}\n== Lobbying activities ==\nIn September 2018, the group opened an office in [[Washington D.C.]], and formally registered as a [[Lobbying in the United States|lobby organization in the United States]], while it was reported to hold meetings with Congressmen from both parties since at least 2015.<ref name=\"Detsch\"/> According to filed reports, Komala spent $7,500 in 2018 and in the next year, penned a $4,000 per month contract with the firm AF International, along with another worth $40,000 with Cogent Law Group.<ref>{{citation|editor-first=Julian|editor-last=Pecquet|url=https://lobbying.al-monitor.com/pulse/iran|title=Annual Overview 2019: Iran opposition buoyed by Trump\u2019s 'maximum pressure' campaign|work=Al-Monitor Lobbying Tracker|date=11 September 2019|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> One-fourth of latter included working on an [[op-ed]], advise to establish a charitable foundation in the U.S., and \"develop\" Wikipedia page.<ref>{{citation|first=Aaron|last=Schaffer|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/02/komala-iranian-kurds-hire-lobbyist-executive-branch-meet-trump.html|title=Iranian Kurdish rebels hire law firm to lobby Trump administration|work=Al-Monitor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206153842/https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/02/komala-iranian-kurds-hire-lobbyist-executive-branch-meet-trump.html|archive-date=6 February 2020|date=5 February 2020|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Komala offshoots}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Iranian exiled parties}}\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Iran]]\n[[Category:Banned political parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Banned Kurdish parties]]\n[[Category:Banned communist parties]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political parties in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Left-wing militant groups in Iran]]\n[[Category:Marxist parties]]\n[[Category:Militant opposition to the Islamic Republic of Iran]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Iran]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Kurdistan Region]]\n[[Category:Political parties of the Iranian Revolution]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Japan]]\n[[Category:Lobbying organizations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Maoist organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Komala Kurdistan's Organization of the Communist Party of Iran}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Komala\n| logo = The Official Logo Of Komala.png\n| logo_size = 100px\n| caption = [[Red star]] combined with the Soviet-style typography of Komala in Persian script<ref name=\"Detsch\">{{citation|last1=Detsch|first1=Jack|title=Kurdish rebels join anti-Iran lobbying fray|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/10/kurdish-rebels-anti-iran-lobbying.html|date=2 October 2018|work=Al-Monitor|accessdate=30 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002234856/https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2018/10/kurdish-rebels-anti-iran-lobbying.html|archive-date=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n| colorcode = Red\n| abbreviation = K\u015eZK\n| leader = [[Abdullah Mohtadi]]<ref name=\"MERIA\"/>\n| foundation = Originally {{start date and age|1969}}<br>Refounded in {{start date and age|2000}}\n| split = [[Komalah (CPI)]] (2000)\n| merged = [[Communist Party of Iran]] (1984)\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]<br>'''Historical:'''<br>[[Maoism]] <small>(1969\u20131979)</small>\n| headquarters = [[Sulaymaniyah]], [[Kurdistan Region]]\n| international = [[Socialist International]] (Observer)<br>[[Progressive Alliance (political international)|Progressive Alliance]]<br>[[Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization|UNPO]]\n| website = [http://www.komalainternational.org/ Komala]\n| country = Iran\n| country2 = Iraq\n| founder = \n| position = [[Far-left politics|Far-left]]\n| national = [[Congress of Nationalities for a Federal Iran]]\n| colors = {{color box|#E70A0A}} Red\n| flag = [[File:Flag of Komala.png|200px]]\n| membership = <1,000 (estimate)<ref name=\"Milburn\"/>\n| membership_year = 2017\n}}\n\nThe '''Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan''' ({{lang-ku|{{lang|fa|\u0643\u06c6\u0645\u0647\u200c\u06b5\u0647\u200c\u06cc \u0634\u06c6\u0695\u0634\u06af\u06ce\u0695\u06cc \u0632\u0647\u200c\u062d\u0645\u0647\u200c\u062a\u0643\u06ce\u0634\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0643\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0626\u06ce\u0631\u0627\u0646}}|Kome\u0142ey \u015eorri\u015fg\u00earr\u00ee Zehmetk\u00ea\u015fan\u00ee Kurdistan\u00ee \u00caran|lit=Society of Revolutionary Toilers of Iranian Kurdistan}}), commonly shortened to '''Komalah''' ({{lang-ku|Kome\u0142e}}; {{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0648\u0645\u0644\u0647}}), is an armed [[communist]] [[ethnic party]] of [[Kurds in Iran]], currently exiled in northern [[Iraq]].<ref name=\"MERIA\"/> \n\nThe group is currently proscribed as a [[terrorist organization]] by [[Japan]], aside from Iran. Since 2018, it is registered [[Lobbying in the United States|lobby in the United States]].\n\nKomalah has been engaged in guerrilla warfare against the Iranian government, notably during the [[1979 Kurdish rebellion in Iran|1979 Kurdish rebellion]] and the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]. It was also [[KDPI\u2013Komala conflict|involved in armed conflict]] against the [[Democratic Party of Iranian Kurdistan]] (KDPI) during the 1980s and early 1990s.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Structure of Kurdish Society and the Struggle for a Kurdish State|author=Hussein Tahiri|year=2007|publisher=Mazda Publications|volume=8|series=Bibliotheca Iranica: Kurdish studies series|isbn=9781568591933|page=144}}</ref> After a long time peace, organisation declared to start armed struggle again in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kurdish party resumes armed struggle against Iran, third party to do so |url=https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/iran/30042017 |website=Rudaw |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe organization has \"no strong influence among the Kurds in Iran\", according to Rodi Hevian.<ref name=\"MERIA\">{{cite journal|author=Rodi Hevian|title=THE MAIN KURDISH POLITICAL PARTIES IN IRAN, IRAQ, SYRIA, AND TURKEY: A RESEARCH GUIDE|url=http://www.rubincenter.org/2013/08/the-main-kurdish-political-parties-in-iran-iraq-syria-and-turkey-a-research-guide/|date=Summer 2013|volume=17|journal=[[Middle East Review of International Affairs]]|number=2|publisher=Rubin Center for Research in International Affairs|location= Herzliya, Israel}}</ref>\n== History ==\nIt is not known when exactly the organization began its activity.<ref>{{citation|first=Ali|last=Ezzatyar|title=The Last Mufti of Iranian Kurdistan: Ethnic and Religious Implications in the Greater Middle East|date=2016|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137563248|page=35}}</ref> According to the account of [[Abdullah Mohtadi]], together with six other Kurdish students in [[Tehran]], he co-founded the group on 27 October 1969 at a secret initiation meeting.<ref>{{citation|first=Ali|last=Ezzatyar|title=The Last Mufti of Iranian Kurdistan: Ethnic and Religious Implications in the Greater Middle East|date=2016|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137563248|page=104}}</ref> [[Ladislav Bittman]] wrote in ''[[The KGB and Soviet Disinformation]]'' that Komala was part of [[KGB]]'s network in Iran, and was founded under financial and ideological influence of [[Soviet Union]].<ref>{{citation|first=Ladislav|last=Bittman|title=The KGB and Soviet Disinformation: An Insider's View|url=https://archive.org/details/TheKGBAndSovietDisinformationLadislavBittman|publisher=Pergamon-Brassey's|year=1983|isbn=9780080315720|page=111}}</ref> [[Edgar O'Ballance]] states that Komala recieved \"help\" from the Soviet KGB.<ref>{{citation|first=Edgar|last=O'Ballance|journal=Military Review: The Professional Journal of the United States Army|title=The Kurdish Factor in the Gulf War|volume=61|number=6|date=June 1981|page=16}}</ref>\n\nThe organization operated underground, and only went into public after the [[Iranian Revolution]] in 1979.<ref name=\"Kreyenbroek and Sperl\"/> In September 1983, the group underwent organizational changes and patterned itself as an orthodox communist party, eventually joining [[Communist Party of Iran]], as its [[Komalah (CPI)|Kurdish wing]].<ref name=\"NE\"/> In 2000, the faction led by [[Abdullah Mohtadi]] split from the latter and styled itself as the \"original\" Komala.<ref>{{citation|last1=Romano|first1=David|last2=Gurses|first2=Mehmet|title=Conflict, Democratization, and the Kurds in the Middle East: Turkey, Iran, Iraq, and Syria|date=2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-40999-7|page=75|edition=1st|doi=10.1057/9781137409997_4}}</ref>\n\nOn grounds that politburo acts non-democratic, the faction led by Omar Ilkhanizade split in October 2007, founding [[Organization of the Toilers of Kurdistan|the faction of reform]].<ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\">{{citation|first1=Hashem|last1=Ahmadzadeh|first2=Gareth|last2=Stansfield|title=The Political, Cultural, and Military Re-Awakening of the Kurdish Nationalist Movement in Iran|journal=Middle East Journal|volume=64|number=1|date=2010|pages=11-27|jstor=20622980}}</ref> On 29 April 2008, another faction led by Abdulla Konaposhi accused Mohtadi of \"non-democratic management\", and expressing dissatifcation to a policy of a cooperation with [[Monarchism in Iran|monarchists]] including [[Reza Pahlavi, Crown Prince of Iran|Reza Pahlavi]], split from the group to establish [[Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan\u2013Reunification Faction|the reunification faction]].<ref name=\"Ahmadzadeh and Stansfield\"/>\n\n== Ideology ==\nThe group is ideologically [[Marxist\u2013Leninist]], therefore it saw itself [[revolutionary]] and transcending ethnic boundaries, unlike rival [[Democratic Party of Iranian Kurdistan]].<ref name=\"NE\">{{cite book|last=Entessar|first=Nader|title=Kurdish Politics in the Middle East|publisher=Lexington Books|location=Lanham|page=49\u201350|year=2010|isbn=9780739140390|oclc=430736528}}</ref> It was predominantly [[Maoist]] during first decade of its activity<ref name=\"NE\"/> and adopted it as a [[Theory of National Struggle|mobilization strategy]] to recruit from peasantry and lower urban class.<ref>{{cite book|last=Romano|first=David|title=The Kurdish Nationalist Movement: Opportunity, Mobilization and Identity|series=Cambridge Middle East studies, 22.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2006|page=233|isbn=978-0-521-85041-4|oclc=61425259}}</ref> However at its first congress held in 1979, the ideology was renounced due to being \"inappropriate to Kurdish conditions in Iran\".<ref name=\"NE\"/> In 1981, the group initiated [[Self-criticism (Marxism\u2013Leninism)|self-criticism]] of its past and concluded that what it needs is \"strong links with the [[proletariat]]\".<ref name=\"Kreyenbroek and Sperl\">{{cite book|editor-last1=Kreyenbroek|editor-first1=Philip G.|editor-last2=Sperl|editor-first2=Stefan|title=The Kurds: A Contemporary Overview|publisher=Routledge|page=143|year=2005|isbn=9781134907663}}</ref>\n\n== Armed activities ==\n{{see also|1979 Kurdish rebellion in Iran|Iran\u2013Iraq War|KDPI\u2013Komala conflict|Western Iran clashes (2016\u2013present)}}\n\n== Designation as a terrorist organization ==\nThe following countries have listed Komola as a [[terrorist organization]]:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n!Country\n!{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Iran}}\n|<ref name=\"Milburn\">{{citation|first=Franc|last=Milburn|title=Iranian Kurdish Militias: Terrorist-Insurgents, Ethno Freedom Fighters, or Knights on the Regional Chessboard?|url=http://www.css.ethz.ch/en/services/digital-library/articles/article.html/41930fa0-6afa-42f3-837b-e343778df613/pdf|publisher=Combating Terrorism Center|via=Eidgen\u00f6ssische Technische Hochschule Z\u00fcrich|date=May 2017|volume=10|issue=5|journal=CTC Sentinel|pages=1\u20132}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Japan}}\n|<ref name=\"JPN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moj.go.jp/psia/ITH/organizations/ME_N-africa/komala.html |script-title=ja:\u30b3\u30de\u30e9|publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (Japan)|Ministry of Justice of Japan]] |language=ja |title=Komaleh\uff0cKumele|access-date=20 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190309091042/http://www.moj.go.jp/psia/ITH/organizations/ME_N-africa/komala.html|archive-date=9 March 2019|url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|}\n== Lobbying activities ==\nIn September 2018, the group opened an office in [[Washington D.C.]], and formally registered as a [[Lobbying in the United States|lobby organization in the United States]], while it was reported to hold meetings with Congressmen from both parties since at least 2015.<ref name=\"Detsch\"/> According to filed reports, Komala spent $7,500 in 2018 and in the next year, penned a $4,000 per month contract with the firm AF International, along with another worth $40,000 with Cogent Law Group.<ref>{{citation|editor-first=Julian|editor-last=Pecquet|url=https://lobbying.al-monitor.com/pulse/iran|title=Annual Overview 2019: Iran opposition buoyed by Trump\u2019s 'maximum pressure' campaign|work=Al-Monitor Lobbying Tracker|date=11 September 2019|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> One-fourth of latter included working on an [[op-ed]], advise to establish a charitable foundation in the U.S., and \"develop\" Wikipedia page.<ref>{{citation|first=Aaron|last=Schaffer|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/02/komala-iranian-kurds-hire-lobbyist-executive-branch-meet-trump.html|title=Iranian Kurdish rebels hire law firm to lobby Trump administration|work=Al-Monitor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206153842/https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/02/komala-iranian-kurds-hire-lobbyist-executive-branch-meet-trump.html|archive-date=6 February 2020|date=5 February 2020|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Komala offshoots}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Iranian exiled parties}}\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Iran]]\n[[Category:Banned political parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Banned Kurdish parties]]\n[[Category:Banned communist parties]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Kurdish political parties in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Left-wing militant groups in Iran]]\n[[Category:Marxist parties]]\n[[Category:Militant opposition to the Islamic Republic of Iran]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Iran]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Kurdistan Region]]\n[[Category:Political parties of the Iranian Revolution]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Japan]]\n[[Category:Lobbying organizations based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Maoist organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Komala_Party_of_Iranian_Kurdistan"}
